{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19319"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19319"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.05,0.1,0.17,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83002"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12053"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"5946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83002"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man who was admitted two days ago is requesting to discharge himself against medical advice. The nurse alerts you to review him. He presented with a three-week history of progressive tingling, numbness and weakness. He does not take any regular medications and has no significant medical history. He admits to recreational nitrous oxide use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination revealed bilateral lower limb hypertonia, sensory ataxia with loss of joint position sense to the thighs and vibration sense to the inguinal region. Pinprick sensation was reduced in both calves. Bilateral ankle dorsiflexion power was 3/5 but otherwise, power is normal. He had broadbased gait and Romberg test was positive. Babinski sign was present bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subacute combined degeneration","Multiple sclerosis","Tabes dorsalis","Chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features in this case are suggestive of vitamin B12 deficiency causing \u003Cstrong\u003Esubacute combined degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E of the spinal cord. The combination of sensory ataxia (dorsal column signs), pyramidal tract signs (hypertonia and extensor plantars), and peripheral neuropathy in a patient with nitrous oxide use strongly supports this diagnosis. The subacute onset over weeks is also typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with episodes of neurological dysfunction separated in time and space. While it can cause similar symptoms, the pattern of progressive symmetrical involvement and dietary history make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy that typically presents with ascending weakness and areflexia. The presence of upper motor neuron signs (extensor plantars and hypertonia) makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E presents with symmetric proximal and distal weakness, sensory symptoms, and reduced or absent reflexes. The presence of upper motor neuron signs and prominent posterior column involvement makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETabes dorsalis\u003C/strong\u003E is a late manifestation of neurosyphilis that can present with sensory ataxia and posterior column signs. However, it typically occurs decades after the initial infection and would be extremely rare in a young person in the modern era.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s nitrous oxide consumption has resulted in vitamin B12 deficiency. Treatment involves urgent vitamin B12 replacement. The patient should be strongly advised against discharge as delayed treatment can lead to permanent neurological damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord presents with progressive sensory ataxia, weakness, and upper motor neuron signs due to vitamin B12 deficiency","Loss of joint position sense and vibration sense with preserved power suggests dorsal column involvement"],"references":["Recreational nitrous oxide neurotoxicity [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2022. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/november/recreational-nitrous-oxide-neurotoxicity"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19319"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68062"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T21:21:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T21:22:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12053"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83002"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag